The Dataset

This dataset comes from Seattle Open Data program that is run by the City of Seattle. The Seattle Open Data is the one who provided the data to the public, but it is the Seattle Public Library who collected the data. They dont list the books ISBN numbers on their data, although it is still a category. The City of Seattle provides this data with the ideology of keeping the people transparent about what happens in Seattle. The dataset is updated monthly, usually around the 6th of each month. They started in 2005, and collect data on both physical media and digital. The physical media can be things like books and video discs, while digital could be ebooks and audiobooks. I think the limitations of this data is that the labeling of subjects is a bit inconsistent.

Psychology Book Checkout Rates Over Time

In this chart I wanted to see if people were checking these items out in digital format but surprisingly, no psychology book was checked out in ebook format. There was a big spike in checkouts in December of 2017. And looking at the dataset it was actually one specific book that was written by a neurologist before his death. As expected there was a low checkout rate during the early pandemic and then a slight surge around 2021 when places started to open up again.

The Rise of Colleen Hoover

In Chart 3, It Ends with Us was the most popular with being 5803 checkouts and its sequel, It Starts with Us released last year, had 1171 checkouts. None of Hoovers other books can compete with the success of It Ends with Us.
